-- 2. Code Optimization: Encapsulating Room Validation

-- Current State: BookingService.apply() contains a long sequence of if statements checking room conditions (gender, capacity, AC, WiFi, etc.). This violates the "Tell, Don't Ask" OOP principle and clutters the service.

-- Optimization: Move this logic inside the Room entity.

-- Java
-- // Inside Room.java
-- public void validateCompatibility(Student student, ApplyRequest request) {
--     if (this.status != RoomStatus.AVAILABLE || this.currentOccupancy >= this.capacity) {
--         throw new IllegalArgumentException("Room is full or unavailable");
--     }
--     if (this.roomGender != student.getGender()) {
--         throw new IllegalArgumentException("Room does not match student gender");
--     }
--     if (this.hasAc != request.hasAc() || this.hasWifi != request.hasWifi()) {
--         throw new IllegalArgumentException("Room amenities do not match preferences");
--     }
-- }

-- // Inside BookingService.apply()
-- // The long chain of 'if' statements is replaced by:
-- locked.validateCompatibility(student, request);
-- Improvement: This makes BookingService much shorter, highly readable, and ensures the domain entity (Room) is responsible for governing its own business rules.

-- Section D: Reflection & Professional Practice
-- 1. Challenges & Solutions

-- Challenge: Managing the lifecycle of security tokens and unpaid bookings without heavily impacting database performance or leaving the system vulnerable to token bloat.

-- Solution: Designed a scheduled background architecture (TokenCleanupService and BookingExpirationScheduler). By utilizing @Scheduled tasks to run batch cleanups automatically at off-peak hours (e.g., 2:00 AM UTC), the database remains optimized and self-maintaining without requiring manual admin intervention or checking tokens synchronously on every user login.

-- 2. Lessons Learned
-- a. Key Concepts Understood Better:

-- JPA Lifecycle Callbacks: Utilizing @PrePersist and @PreUpdate in the Student and Booking entities to automatically manage createdAt and updatedAt timestamps removed boilerplate code and guaranteed data integrity.

-- Transactional Boundaries: Understanding how @Transactional works, specifically how it wraps an entire method into a single database unit of work so that if the payment creation fails, the entire room booking rolls back safely.

-- Global API Exception Routing: Learning how @ExceptionHandler cleanly separates business logic (throwing exceptions) from presentation logic (formatting HTTP error responses).

-- b. What I Would Do Differently:
-- If starting over, I would introduce Data Transfer Object (DTO) Projections earlier at the repository layer. Currently, the system loads entire large entities (like Student with their full profiles and password hashes) just to check minor details. Fetching only the explicitly required fields directly from the database query would make the system more memory-efficient as the user base scales.